Password Security Review
What makes a strong password?

A strong password should be long, unique, and difficult to guess. It should contain uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters while avoiding personal information.

Why should passwords be unique?

Using unique passwords ensures that if one account is compromised, attackers cannot gain access to other accounts using the same password.

What is Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)?

Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) is a security method that requires users to verify their identity using two or more authentication factors, such as a password and a verification code sent to a mobile device.

Risks of Password Reuse
Multiple accounts can be compromised.
Increased risk of identity theft.
Easier credential stuffing attacks.
Financial loss.
Loss of personal information.
Password Policy
Use at least 12–16 characters.
Include uppercase and lowercase letters.
Include numbers.
Include special characters.
Avoid personal information.
Never reuse passwords.
Enable MFA wherever available.
Change passwords immediately if compromised.
Use a password manager.
Update important passwords periodically.